        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3568070927" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10080830514644644156">This was a re-read. This time around it was for the longer text.<br/><br/>I like the longer text better. It elaborates more on what Julian of Norwich saw during her visions. <br/><br/>While I was reading this I used a copy of the Wycliffe Bible as reference work. Anytime scripture was mentioned I looked it up in that translation. For me it wasn’t that difficult to read. But, this is coming from a person who had to memorize Chaucer while in High School. So something you can try, is to have both the Wycliffe and King</span>
  <span id="freeText10080830514644644156" style="display:none">This was a re-read. This time around it was for the longer text.<br /><br />I like the longer text better. It elaborates more on what Julian of Norwich saw during her visions. <br /><br />While I was reading this I used a copy of the Wycliffe Bible as reference work. Anytime scripture was mentioned I looked it up in that translation. For me it wasn’t that difficult to read. But, this is coming from a person who had to memorize Chaucer while in High School. So something you can try, is to have both the Wycliffe and King James open side by side while reading the quoted scriptures. Reading the scriptures can help put you into the frame of mind that Julian was in while experiencing her visions and writing the text.<br /><br />This book is also considered to by a “Christian Classic”. So give this one a go and see what it means to you.<br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
